author: @seberry1
text: I thought this film was poorly written and forgettable. First off, no "large cocoon" would have survived the nuclear detonation of the M-class star freighter Nostromo. Second, how could a band of teenage misfits commandeer the Corbelan IV without being detected and stopped by the security forces of a clearly repressive slave colony regime on LV-410? It doesn't make sense, then it gets worse. As if lacking the imagination to not simply re-cycle the same tired, overused elements from the Alien franchise (face hugging and chest bursting and all the rest), Team √Ålvarez goes on to do exactly that. Only in this predictable recycling the aliens look silly, like lobsters scurrying around on meth. I thought the original Alien film was a masterpiece but it was a film that was true to itself; it was nuanced with mood and mature relationships, not to mention that the plot points had an impelling credibility and focus. My recommendation: don't waste your precious time.

author: @chattyman4740
text: SPOILERS - Yeah, this movie was a disappointment in the end. It was ok, but it was just a rehash of scenes from all of the other movies, the set of Alien, the lift shaft set piece was just the end of Aliens, the close encounter bit was lifted from Alien 3, the hybrid creature was lifted from Resurrection, the black substance and the Android stuff from Prometheus, some annoying and boring characters you didn't care about, bringing back Ian Holm was interesting but it looked weird and absurd. It doesn't add anything new to the franchise, just more running around in corridors in the dark screaming, the end. The only saving grace - was David Jonsson who was brilliant and acted the rest of the lightweight cast off the screen - he has a huge career ahead of him in MUCH better pictures.

1)Prometheus (2012)

4)Alien: Isolation (Video Game)
5)Alien: Romulus (2024, just aired in cinemas)
6)Aliens (1986)
7)Alien 3 (1992)
8)Alien: Resurrection (1997)

author: @thomashynes4042
text:
There are MANY problems with this movie - my complaints are the following

1: For the first 10-15 minutes of the film, the characters with a Heavy British Accent, I could not understand a single word they said. the opening of the movie is chaotic, there is too much going on, and the recovery of "materials" is not made clear other than the name spread across some of the debris. It was NOT clear as to who was recovering these materials, as I thought it was the kids, and yes let us call them kids ... there was NO clear definition of the who what or why.

2: The speed at which some of these "ALIENS" morph was so out of touch with the original movie and its follow-up ALIENS that I was like WHAT WAIT you telling me in 60 seconds the creature goes from a face hugger to a fully formed Alien in the first two movies the element of time was needed, even with ALIEN3

3: Having been shot on DIGITAL made the movie lose a certain quality that the Alien, Aliens, and Alien3 had, that grainy look, The Film just captures images so differently than Digitial, that I have to say did this movie an injustice.

4: The HEAVY reliance on scenes, and some character lines that were used from Alien, Aliens, Alien3, and Alien Ressurection was way over the top. One can sit and watch and say YEP that's Aliens, Yep that is from Alien3, Yep that is from Alien, Yep that's from Alien Resurrection.

5: I saw the movie at a refurbished AMC theater in my area where everything was updated from just even a few years ago, new seats, new speakers, new screens installed...and this was all done previously in 2005 and redone again at what must have been a phenomenal cost in 2021 - this observation is mostly a review of the theater itself, but it was WAY to loud, I came out with my ears buzzing and all numb.

Over the MOVIE is okay, but in all honesty, this was the first time I went back to the movie theater in some 10 years, one could certainly wait for it to be available on a streaming service.....SAVE YOUR MONEY!

author: @joewright9879
text:
Two strikes against this rehash of Alien right off the bat:

1. Sigourney Weaver‚Äôs Ellen Ripley ain‚Äôt in it.

2. Disney‚Äôs producing it.

Number 2 was enough for me to ignore it, but then I saw the trailer. When a trailer doesn‚Äôt hold your interest it‚Äôs best to keep your card in your wallet.

That they couldn‚Äôt figure out how to put Sigourney Weaver in the cast shows poor planning and even poorer judgment. I guess they figure youngsters won‚Äôt be familiar with the previous Alien movies.

But what the hey, Disney‚Äôs done such a bang up job with Star Wars, maybe they‚Äôve applied the same magic formula to Alien: Remus.

author: @mremu
text: This is one of maybe 5 movies that I have really looked forward to seeing in the last 20 years. Fede cut this and the teaser himself and it shows. I love the sound design! I don't know why, but I loved the littlest things like the deep guitar strum when the xeno is introduced and I loved the crackling sound of the spaceship approaching the space station at the very start of the first teaser. I really hope this is an example for studios to get directors that actually care about the IP and let them do their job without interfering. The main thing studios should push for is practical effects done right over doing cgi for everything. The biggest reason the cost of films these days are so insane is from too much cgi when it's so much more expensive and looks worse than doing practical sprinkled with cgi. You get better acting from all the actors when everything isn't a green screen too. And all the set designs are absolutely stunning! I would have paid anything to walk through them...

author: @Paelorian
text:
Another sequel that's just an inferior remake of the first movie! The best sequel was Aliens because it tried something different, was well-directed, and had strong character development. The rest of thr sequels are remakes of the first movie with more stupid characters, but at least Prometheus was more ambitious and showed a lot of lost potential for a better, more interesting movie that they ultimately steered away from to deliver more of the same. But at least David was an interesting character and provided some continuity and character development from one film to the next, something these films need in the absence of Ripley.

This movie looks like the first movie but with more computer effects and worse characters and acting and directing. Junk. This franchise and universe deserves more interesting and original movies. The lore is interesting but all we ever see filmed are scared idiots running down dimly-lit spaceship corridors. Slight variations of the same xenomorph and facehugger and chestburster scenes in every movie. How about a more thoughtful and psychological entry in the series where people talk and say interesting things and the implications of a hostile alien presence are discussed? Sometimes I wonder why I expect more of this franchise when all it wants to show us is the same violent scenes over and over forever.

author: @WormholeJim
text:
I don't care what anyone else says, I just want to know what David's up to with all those "infused" colonists in cryostatis. And how that all ties up with the derelicted ship on LV-426 beaming out, not a distress signal, but a warning to stay away.

But OK, I'm up for a wham-bam adventure, too (even, as I can already hear the internet fans sharpening their axes over how it's still not exactly perfectly the way they want it. What with no Hicks or Newt or any of that whole alternate storyline). Just, please don't forget about that story you were telling, mr. Scott. We're several hungry to know what it all ends with, we're just not all that loud about it.

author: @TiddlyBlinx
text:
Ah yes, mixed breeding. Nothing has been so effective in comfortably making the natural qualities of a creature less potent.

What Weyland is in his world, Hollywood is in our world. Hollywood holds about the same position, money, and power as Weyland does in the movies. But these fancy folk share something in common with the average intelligent, millionaire rancher; they know exactly what they are doing with their cattle. So if you find that the latest propaganda is hinting towards you hitching up with a certain demographic, think to yourself, "what is it about me that they are they trying to get rid of? Is it good or bad? Should they be the ones deciding which of my qualities belong in the world and in my children? Do they qualify to be herding me?"

Because they think like ranchers, I found Doja Cat's "Cow" song to be especially insulting to the masses. It was like watching a giant pig party where the celebrities tricked simpler and kinder people into calling themselves cows all day.

Please stop letting them do this to you. Find someone like yourself, your parents, and your grandparents. Have beautiful children. Teach them about Jesus Christ. Teach them about how they are the future, how they come from a long and unbroken bloodline, how they are a living vessel for Godliness, knowledge, and culture. Teach them that their actions shape the world, so be the change they want to see. Don't be someone's cow.

text:
I felt Prometheus was the best comeback of all of them since the 90s. They had so much to play off of for the sequel‚Ä¶but they put out the follow up, and it just didn‚Äôt seem right. Felt rushed to tie it all together, for a lower budget flick.

They could have def made Prometheus 1-3, and if done as well as the 1st one‚Ä¶I‚Äôd eat it up and go to the theater to watch. But Alien Covenant as a follow up was weak. This looks like a direct to stream movie.

I don‚Äôt get how they finally made a great Aliens movie in 2012, and couldn‚Äôt follow up the same suspense and quality. I wish they could have spun off it, and delivered more of the same but with new worlds and tied in lore.

author: @gmzogga
text:
To everyone complaining about "diversity" and "TikTok Generation":
Diversity: Roll a dice with 10 sides to determine what people to include in a film. With a chance of 40% ('cause only 60% of the US population white) you will get a non-white character. How is that even remotely "way too diverse"? Do you really feel like a film is bad as soon as it shows young characters with modern hairstyles?
TikTok Generation: Do you really want to see horror films with actors that are only above 40yo? As long as there is no weird force of the current pop-culture (I'm looking at you "Unhinged") I don't see a problem with choosing actors under 30.
How shallow can u be to judge a horror(!) film only by the looks of the characters, instead of looking at the overall quality of the characters... Fede Alvarez is a mastermind, guys. Don't have faith in Disney, but have a little faith in Fede.

author: @Malachor01
text:
Sorry. Not sold.

As someone whose favourite movie of all time is Aliens (the greatest movie ever made, period, without debate or question) I can tell immedietely they're attempting to hijack it, with a cast that just doesn't look like it's going to work. The minimalistic showcase is something I can appreciate however. If it has minimal CGI, realistic models, proper ambience/atmosphere, and the character development is on point however, I will eat my words.

I'll go see it because Aliens movies are awesome, but nothing can (or will) come close to - let alone top - the God of films: Aliens.

text:
This seems so unnecessary. Like the prequel to The Thing.
"Let's show what happened to the colonists on LV-426! It'll be so cool! We can fill in all the blanks fans have been demanding for so many years! Like explaining how they set up atmospheric machines to make the air breathable and what natural resources are on this "rock with no indigenous life" that the Company/government decided was important enough to colonize for some reason!"
"Yeah! And we can reveal that there's a derelict alien spaceship that someone named Burke instructs a four-person family to go investigate which has a little girl whom her brother calls Rebecca but her parents call Newt for some reason. And how the other colonists see the facehugger on his face and think: Well, we need to send more people to that ship to get to the bottom of this!"
"Wait! We have to come up with a plausible way for them to capture twelve facehuggers in vats of solution without getting attacked by them in the process!"
"Right! And there can be an indifferent android who seems to care but not care about all the deaths occurring around him and calls the lifeforms 'fascinating' and calmly/politely tells people to 'run' but offers no other helpful solutions and winds up getting destroyed before any type of rescue can arrive."
"Oh! And we need to show who took a bite out of that doughnut and then left the room for some reason!"
"Perfect! Let's do this!"

text:
While the trailer makes the film look decent and I will try to keep an open mind, there is one thing that really bothers me:
In the original ALIEN Weaver and Cartwright were the youngest actor's with 30 years old.
In ALIEN: ROMULUS the oldest actor (David Jonsson) is of that age. The others are all significantly younger. To me these are all children.
I understand, that this way it is easier for marketing the film to the main audience still going to the theaters, but I find it completely unbelievable for the plot.
Having been born 7 years before the first film of the franchise has been released, the age of the characters is off-putting to me.

author: @blehman18066
text:
I'm 56 years old.. I saw the original Alien movie in a theater back in the day..
No offense meant to legendary producer / director Ridley Scott, who is still trying to tell a story after all these decades..
But, like Kellogg's Corn Flakes - the original is still the best!!!!
I have seen every single Alien movie over the years, and I wil say this..
NOTHING comes even close to the original..
The sense of dread, even from the first few minutes.
The feeling you had, watching the crew of the Nostromo deal with events and become more afraid with each passing minute..
You - the viewer - felt like you were trapped - with them - looking for a way out..
Don't get me wrong.. I enjoyed all the sequels..
But Ridley Scott saying that 'Romulus' takes the Alien 'franchise' back to its roots?
This entire franchise was built on Ripley and her fight against the alien..
And Scott just blowing off the sequels shows that he has forgotten the very reason we went to the threaters back in the day in the first place..
Just saying..

text:
Feels cringey. It feels like it's gonna fail like a typical slasher film where teenagers doing stupid and run. Probably because of the gen z antics. Whenever you see some young actors, you'll immediately imagine them to be part of the Gen Z actions and antics. Too much tiktok affected my view of them I guess. Like the only thing they're missing here is to have a selfie, outfit of the day, or a tiktok dance with the alien. ü§£

Oh and that "Run" like wtf cringe af. Like what the heck is this. Are they trying to replicate a classic "say run then the villain will run". Like the Jurassic Park 3 where the spino looks at them and Dr. Grant says run, and the dino runned. ü§£

and especially the "Sum in a wotah. I dunno, ders sumthing in da focking wotah". It's like you're in a future, working on menial job, and colonizing a planet. Why the heck you're speaking like a noble or a royalty. It gives me goosebumps in a bad way. ü§£

author: @brandonspain12345
text: This trailer was probably the first time since maybe Alien¬≥ that the Xenomorphs are legit scary again. The sound mixing is really haunting, and the thumping sound only to reveal it's a glowing chest burger breaking through the ribcage is so brilliantly edited and just a creepy reveal. It also has great shots and photography that feels unique from the other films. (Actually, some shots remind me alot of Alien: Isolation. Which is really cool. It seems it's doing what Alien Covenant failed to do which is to recapture the original movie while doing it's own new spin. It's also nice to see some practical effects (in a trailer no less.) For this alone, this is definitely gonna be one of the best Alien movie since Aliens. üòÅ

author: @yourmothercalledshesaid
text:
If there is a Romulus lab, then there should be a Remus lab, or twin lab, as well. Just a thought while studying the origins of the word 'Romulus' and trying to predict what themes will show up from the word's useage.

Also, the large terraforming station shown in the first few seconds of the trailer, this isn't supposed to be LV-426 or Acheron is it? Either way, it looks like Weyland-Yutani tech. The breaching of the Romulus lab reminds me, a little,, of the William Gibson script for Alien 3 where protagonists break in and try and sabotage the labs experimenting on Xenomorphs.

Just a few loose thoughts. Overall, I think the cinematography and art direction gives the trailer a great Scott/Cameron vibe. I really hope this picture does for the franchise what Prey did for Predator.

author: @ModernDayRenaissanceMan
text:
I'm torn. I grew up on the original trilogy.
Alien is a masterpiece.
Aliens is somehow BETTER.
Alien 3 is an underrated movie.

Everything after that is trash & I don't claim it.

This movie seems to basically be a copycat of Aliens. Similar visuals & formula that works. So yes.... You kids today MIGHT get a good movie, BUT it won't be original.

I don't know if it will push the franchise forward. At this point I think that the classics will always remain better. You'll never beat Jurassic Park, Braveheart, Gladiator, & so on down the list no matter how many sequels or remakes they try.

Let's just focus on other things like Thundercats or He-Man that we CAN improve on. Voltron still needs a live action movie. I can name 50 things... Deathlands as a TV show.

Do better Hollywood

author: @HeyThreshold
text:
00:52 that is the Lupa Capitolina, a bronze sculpture depicting a scene from the legend of the founding of Rome.
The sculpture shows a she-wolf suckling the mythical twin founders of Rome, Romulus and Remus.
The sculpture is probably Etruscan, probably dating to the fifth century BC, albeit exact dating is still disputed, with the twins added in the late 15th century AD. The she-wolf is still the symbol of Rome and the species she belongs to, Canis lupus italicus (a subspecies of the grey wolf native to the Italian Peninsula), is unofficially considered the national animal of Italy.

author: @sylviecharlois1165
text: It looks like this movie has taken the "taking it back to its roots" trope very litterally... This looks like a straight up copy of Alien, down to the title reveal and the partial use of the catch phrase "In space no one can hear you scream". Visually it also looks like a carbon copy of Alien. The only thing that feels slightly different is a younger cast, and some pretty graphic shots of that pesky facehugger. It's both intriguing and a let-down. What made Alien so special was both its new approach, its slow pace and its mystery, since pretty much nothing happened for about an hour, and then very little was shown, apart from the famous chestburster scene. Too tame for today's audiences, who want to see everything ?

Aliens: Rockin 80s sci-fi action.

Alien Resurrection: Gimmicks galore!
Prometheus: Hey let's ruin all the mystique of the original, inject a bunch of stupid lore, and have characters that act like total idiots!

Alien Romulus: Let's sell out the remaining 5% of this franchise's soul!

text: Production values look great, the spirit and vibe seem to be in line with the original good movies, BUT what is the point of new Alien movies at this point?  There's nothing new to learn about the Xenomorph.  Monster movies stop being so scary when you know everything about the movie monster.  So my question is really - why bother?  Who is going to go see this movie in cinemas?  I love Alien, and Aliens is an all time favourite.  I saw Alien 3 and above in cinemas (and regretted most of them...).  But unless reviews come out saying it's amazingly good and bring something new and original, I am not interested at all.  Just let it go man.

author: @gavinelder3933
text:
Good part of this is borrowed from James Camerons Aliens, the atmosphere processor, camera angles showing the acid melt through multiple floors.

The classic Med Lab scene where Ripley has the face hugger try to plant itself, same angles here...

Not complaining, might actually be good this time around.

Covenant was grim, a mish Mash of all the Alien franchise rolled into one.

Please don't have a scene where the beast meets its end cos somebody "blew it outta the goddamn airlock!!"

I want something unique, this might be it, can only hope...

Oh, and a big hint to the return of the Queen Ant, she's a big mother!

Speaking of which, Bill Paxton, what an actor, the fear seemed all too real the way that Hudson projected his character.
Bill Paxton had so much more to offer us in way of movie gold.
Taken far too soon, peace big fella.

text:
I dunno... the trailer didn't take me. I believe much better has been done to the Predator's franchise, Pray was absolutely very special to me, very different and unique compared to the fist, which will remain one of my favourite movies with the best character and character's background ever made in the sci-fi genre, a gem on its own. Maybe because there were Native Americans involved and my personal bond with them is always tight and strong.
In case of Alien: Romulus... I really dunno what to expect, it didn't give me good vibes... I'm concerned the story is flat and the characters irrelevant to the narrative. I hope I'm wrong, because I love Alien, I love Giger... and I honestly believe Alien and Predator worlds should collide again, after Alien vs Predator I felt left orphan of the next chapter of that story, I was really going to be totally invested in what could have happened in the Predators' ship and I was dreaming on about finding myself casted into Predators' planet, that's the new place, the new scenario I still wish is coming next, sooner or later!

author: @bluechiefawesome5587
text:
Ugh! I feel the Alien movies have become glorified teenage slasher flicks.
I miss the mystery and the slow-paced tension of the original. It was a sort of cosmic horror about the evil lurking in the darkest corner of space, a monstrosity incomprehensible to the human mind, that was better off never being brought to light. That's what Alien used to be. Nowadays, it's basically Jurassic Park in space.

author: @EnigmaHood
text: Little disappointed. I wanted a sequel to Prometheus, a real sequel, not Covenant which cow towed to a vocal minority. This just looks like a generic action movie. Prometheus established a lore that was thought provoking, and made people ask questions that we're still not getting answers to. A brainless action flick is what the vocal minority clamored for, and we got Covenant because of it, and this is going even further away from the mystique of how the Xenomorphs were created in the first place. Maybe the trailer is misleading, and the movie does explore some of those themes, but I doubt it, and the trailer didn't do anything to make us believe otherwise.

text:
After Alien VS Predator, Prometheus and Covenant, I don't have the slightest confidence in this movie. This trailer shows only one thing: they've got the audacity and they're about to come up with yet another reheated reboot, with no soul, no creativity, no contribution to the universe whatsoever, just to capitalise on the name of a well-known franchise, to once again catch the idiots like a flycatcher.

Go and see FURIOSA. Creative, unique, singular, fresh and delightful SF.

it's going to be another sausage fest with facehuggers and an alien in a confined environment, ike all the others, the same script will unfold before your very eyes. It's unbelievable that you'd want to hype people and end coming up with a trailer that leaves you neurasthenic - except for the accouphene effect.

author: @DenisMares126
text: So this absolutely took my breath away for this movie, I was really looking forward to it, but after this amazingly incredible trailer, I am now watching with my mouth open, how is it even possible to repeat the qualities of the first two legendary aliens, which were shot by big director names like Ridley Scott and James Cameron, both of these brilliant directors  no one can top this series anymore, but Fede √Ålvarez can proudly join them, because after what he showed in this trailer, he is not trying to make a mere remake or reboot that will only exploit and steal what once worked here, but √Ålvarez is changing  exactly the rules of the game he brings to this universe a film that is set in the timeline between the first and second part so it fills a big gap and also takes into account the highly acclaimed game Alien Isolation which is also canon in this universe and thus tries more these films and the game  to connect and take something from everyone because Fede √Ålvarez is an incredible and loyal fan of these films and grew up watching them, so when he made this film he could not decide whether to shoot this film in a more intimate style like in the first or a far more spectacular and action style like in the second and  above all, not one of these films is better than the other, both are of the same quality, and that is why he decided to create a hybrid between these films, he will take something from each of them, such as coziness and magnificence, as well as futuristic technologies, which are also very different in these two films, but at the same time he will add  and his completely new, fresh, brutal Gore direction, which resurrects the entire series, and I was very pleased with the fact that this director mainly uses practical effects and not just cgi, which is now everywhere and rarely looks as believable as the practical effects, this alone proves from what  he has respect and reverence for the original films of this series, thanks to this the alien again looks slimy disgusting and very believable and palpable √Ålvarez turns him again into the iconic terrifyingly beautiful biomechanical monster he also made me very happy with the addition of new technology to recognize the alien in the human body that shines through the ribcage  and shows this disgusting parasite this seems very iconic and Fede √Ålvarez is mainly known for his love of gore brutal and disgusting scenes and he certainly didn't skimp on it here and this nice detail with this new technology just proves that there is no better director for invaders than Fede √Ålvarez he  it expands this universe but at the same time sticks to the originally set rules and thus pays honor and respect to the original films üí™ü´Ä‚ú® by the way, I'm a big fan of The Intruder and I can proudly say that this is really about what loyal fans like  they waited a long timeüí™ü´Ä‚ú®

author: @Robert44444444
text: Here's the thing‚Ä¶ the whole concept of the face hugger, humans serving as hosts while a parasitic alien life form gestates until it bursts free killing the human host, and on & on it goes‚Ä¶ that was all very novel in 1978. The follow-up "Aliens" is pretty universally seen as an even superior treatment of the whole fictional narrative. In my view, after that it wasn't until 2012's "Prometheus" until things got interesting again with a shift to Wallen, David and the 'Engineers' and why humans were 1st created and then targeted for extinction via the Engineers "bio weapon".  "Covenant" picked up and continued this with a bit too much of the return of the "boogie-man gonna getcha"‚Ä¶ now with this film there seems to be a near abandonment of what's up with David and the Engineers and a return to Xenomorphs picking off crew members one by one on a ship(s)‚Ä¶ boring.

author: @_ClericalError_
text:
I mean, it looks like it will be one of the movies of all time.

It is only a trailer so I can only judge so much, but it looks like the casting director raided the local university acting classes for the cast, carefully chosen to represent as many ethnicities as possible, complete with a mish-mash of accents to add some intersectionality points.

Whoever cut the trailer is not doing the movie any favors, they wield callback scenes like a bludgeon, and the small snippets of dialog they give us are generic and empty. They've fallen into the trope of interpreting "oppressive environment" to mean "light sources don't exist."

I love the Alien franchise, but I'm also in my 40s, and the trailer at least looks like it was a movie made intentionally to be aggressively unappealing to me and many people my age.

author: @Radonatos
text:
"Are you sure you wanna do this?"
Good question. I liked Alvarez' works back from when I saw his giant robot invasion short on YT.
But the damage done by Scott with Prometheus and Covenant doesn't really permit a "back to the roots" imo - the first Alien movie wasn't only about the claustrophobic survival against a perfect non-terrestrial organism hunting you, but also about how scary and bizarre alien life may be elsewhere in the universe.
So I'm split about this, I hope that Alvarez will somehow navigate around this, and that Scott's influence as producer will not be noticeable.

author: @Flippiedeflap
text: There are some elements that I see which I don't like. Shots that have been made that way to make the action seem more cool. Insane inertia shots of the facehugger is one, the face that you can shine a light through your entire body to see the alien growing inside is another. And yeah that you actually see the face hugger try to insert the whatever the word for it is is really cool, yet why does it seem to do this reverse movement, pauze and hold, and then "charge" into his face as if it's building up momentum? That's what it's fingers are for. It's quick and agile, powerful with it's fingers and tails. Other than that it's frail and has the acid blood as defense. Why go over the top with these shots? Totally unnecessary.

author: @robertomata7563
text: The claustrophobic scenario of the original worked because it was about a group of white-collar workers in space who just happened to come across alien life. Aliens worked because it took the concept of alien life and turned it into a war/survival story that added the only survivor of the original. Prometheus worked because it was about a group of explorers trying to find their creators. And, Covenant worked because it took the concept of creation from Prometheus and turned it into an endless exploration of the horrors behind it. Romulus looks like another claustrophobic space movie offering nothing new.

I just loved this!
I really hope the movie live up to this excelente trailer.

Looks like a true return to the core of the franchise, focusing on the Xenomorph. This wouldn't happen in Alien movies for a while now;
Despite everything, I really like Prometheus and Convenant. This debate about mankind created by the Engeneers, and the dynamcs between humans and androids, that creator x creation thing its so fascinanting.
But, at least for me, Alien was always about Xenomorph. The true fear caused by it, the psicologic pressuare it has on the people. This is whats this all about... and call me naive, but I could see this on this trailer.
I hope not be disapointed
